The black box in your car?
While American road designers are struggling to find money to repair the crumbling highway network, many are starting to see the solution in a small black box that easily fits into your car’s dashboard.
Devices that track every mile a motorist walks and pass this information on to authorities are at the heart of a controversial effort by Washington and state planning authorities to rebuild America’s outdated system of financing major roads.
Usually, the tedious design of motorways suddenly sparked an intense debate and the formation of various associations.
The Libertarians met with groups of environmentalists and lobbied for the government to use these tiny lockers to record miles travelled and perhaps even where you were going – and then use this information to build a tax return.
The tea party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has mentioned a number of privacy concerns.
And while Congress cannot agree on whether to proceed, some states are not expecting anything.
They explore how they can move over the next decade to a system in which the driver pays for a kilometer of the road he is driving on.
Thousands of motorists have already taken black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real necessity for our nation.
“It’s not a matter of choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California State Administration Association, which plans to start tracking every California motorist in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
This is what this technology is for.
The impetus is the fact that the Road Trust Fund, financed by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations, is at the bottom.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as before.
Cars can travel many more miles per gallon.
The federal tax of 18.4 cents per gallon has not increased in the last 20 years.
Due to the current high price of gasoline, politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by a single cent.
“A gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed a tracking device in 500 cars to test this per-kilometre payment system.
"In the long run, this seems like the most logical alternative," he said.
Experts call it a user fee based on the number of kilometers travelled.
It’s no surprise that urban liberals like the idea, because taxes can be used to change driver behavior patterns, which can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Californian planners look to this system when planning strategies to meet the goals set out in ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster (representative of Pennsylvania), chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most functional long-term alternative.
Reason Foundation’s free market leaders are also in favor of drivers paying for mileage.
“It’s not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The initiative is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who in 2011 urged Congress to move towards paying per kilometer.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would involve about 10,000 cars.
However, the House of Representatives rejected the proposal, due to concerns from rural lawmakers representing parts of the population, whose daily life often means walking many miles to work outside the city.
However, several states and cities are still making progress on their own.
The most zealous is Oregon, which included 5,000 drivers in the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon start paying the state a mileage tax instead of a gasoline tax.
Nevada has already completed the pilot project.
New York is exploring the project.
Illinois is trying to do this to a limited extent on trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 state transport ministries, along with coastal states in the east (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is studying how they can implement the change.
However, this concept does not only have supporters.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with the device, drivers were concerned that the government was able to monitor their every move.
“Worrying about Big Brother tracking and similar issues was a big issue,” said Alauddin Khan, who leads the strategy and operations management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't something people wanted.
As the trial project continued, the American Civil Liberties Union in Nevada warned on its website: “It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-fledged tracking devices.”
There is no need to build a huge cumbersome technological infrastructure, which will inevitably expand to record the daily trips and arrivals of individuals.
Nevada is among the few states that are trying to find affordable technology that would allow the state to track how many kilometers the car travels, but not exactly when and where.
If you can do that, Khan said, the public will be more calm.
The pursuit of such technology led some state agencies to a small California company called True Mileage.
Initially, the company was not involved in the action to assist the government in taxing drivers.
She wanted to break into the emerging market for legal liability insurance, where drivers would pay based on how much they drove.
But this device, which it tests, attracts the attention of road network designers, because it does not use GPS and delivers only a limited amount of information, which is regularly recorded using a modem.
“People will be more willing to go if you don’t track their speed and their location,” says Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
A number of major errors have occurred in some of these pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers a choice.
They can choose devices with or without GPS.
Or they do not have to take any equipment and instead decide to pay a flat fee based on the average mileage of all residents of the state.
In other places, they hope that the cautious public will accept this concept if the device is able to do more, not less.
In the city of New York, traffic officials are trying to develop a taxation device that would be equipped to pay extra parking hours, to provide mileage insurance, and to collect data on other drivers’ speed so that motorists can avoid traffic jams.
“Motors will be willing to get involved because of the value of the benefits offered to them,” the city’s projection document said.
However, some transport planners would like to know if all the discussions about paying per kilometer are not just a huge proxy problem.
Officials from the Metropolitan Transportation Committee in the San Francisco Bay Area say Congress could easily solve the problem of the bankrupt Road Trust Fund by raising the tax on gasoline.
A one-off or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid or other vehicles that do not consume much fuel, so they will pay a fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when you have enough aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Committee on Legislation and Public Affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will be worried about their privacy and a lot of other things.
