George Kerevan: Divided Europe Gives Scots a Choice
Another day, another scary story about independence.
This time, there is a warning that the condition for an independent Scotland to join the EU would be its accession to Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport controls at Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
The truth is that the Strathclyde newspaper mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but, as might be expected, it did not make headlines.
Nor did anyone mention that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws if it suits them.
Since Scotland is not currently in Schengen, the offer of continued mismatch would be a cheap concession to Brussels in return for whatever they really want from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
I heard the journalistic duck that “independence means passport controls” at least 40 years ago.
Yet there is an interesting thought in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe at all?
Why trade the London ham for the Brussels ham, especially now?
This is a true European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
As a result of the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, they are gaining influence from parties dedicated to resistance to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded this year – came out of nowhere and already looted nearly five million votes in the September federal election, essentially sweeping the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
On home soil there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, coupled with a tight jacket drawn on national economies by clinging to a common currency, has led many to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments managing high budget deficits – this was true only in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of the euro that blocks its members at exchange rates favourable to German exporters – and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only way to do this is to cut revenues and public spending – as Germany is urging.
Behind the current problems with the budget and the currency, there is a deeper cause of Europe's malaise.
As a result of the “green” energy policy backed by Brussels – a code to support French and German companies at the expense of consumers – European industry is paying twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as is the case in the United States.
This is a paralyzing disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even all the freezing of wages in the world would not prevent the European petrochemical industry from trampling on cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smoldering uprising, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool that would keep Germany in check and allow Paris to rise to the level of Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a sign of political legitimacy, and has enforced its own economic policy in Europe and left the worn-out French economy to its fate.
Result: Marine Le Pen’s right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a major additional election and pushed the ruling Socialists to third place.
The front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – an early warning to British Labour that they cannot conclude that a split on the right will automatically have a positive effect on the left.
How does Le Pen deal with her newfound popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use next year’s European elections to create an anti-European bloc against the common currency across the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in this election, which is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in its history.
At the same time, I think that in the near future the growing anti-European feeling and attitude against the common currency will unite and the euro will be destroyed.
The EU will not disappear, but rather turn into something more free in the sense of the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle preferred.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and to cling to the United States.
However, Washington’s heightened interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
Where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be a region (in principle) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – that includes telling Berlin and Brussels when to leave us alone.
I assume that Scotland would do well in a relaxed order of Europe, provided it retains its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and keep our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is, strangely enough, the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition stance against cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the subsequent coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence only to adopt austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: matured earlier
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
Physical changes don’t mean puberty is approaching.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are behind this.
Experts say that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be an epidemic of obesity.
The trend of early puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children’s health and family issues.
Should a mother be frightened when her daughter begins to grow breasts and pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
“I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that this is usually not a sign of rapid development toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Over the past 40 years, however, there has been only a small shift in the age at which the first menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, up from 12.75 in 1970.
“When the breasts start to develop, it takes at least two to three years for the first menstruation to occur,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of “Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
The most reliable test of how puberty will proceed is time.
It is discussed what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "prematurely mature".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – which can be closely monitored by children’s doctors.
A faster growth may be a reason for an endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stopping growth and stunting in adulthood.
Recommendations for medications and hormone treatments depend on the child’s age, rate of development, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosociological aspects are also important.
When it comes to drug use, Kaplowitz is cautious, but recognizes that “repressing puberty can alleviate a girl’s behavioral problems and her feelings of being different from her peers.”
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried she might get pregnant or how she'll manage her hygiene," Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were indications and we talked about menstruation, it was not prepared emotionally.
She came home from school frightened and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is still no consistent set of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped carry out a study on girls between the ages of 6 and 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations are different.
From a global perspective, it seems that patterns of early puberty are influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although boys have facial and pubic hair at a young age, the trend towards full bloom of early puberty is not as clear as girls.
Other doctors attending the conference of the American Association of Pediatric Physicians (AAP) added more complexity to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
“We have to be careful about how we identify the actual onset of puberty,” said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeo Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their child’s doctor on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you'd expect," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, your child will probably respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need to be reassured that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
