A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
More tests are needed before human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell School of Medicine in New York says the first signs are good.
“We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but found that their nicotine addiction is so strong as to overcome all current approaches,” Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been assembled to carry the genetic information to create anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a smooth stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, thus preventing the smoker from getting nicotine interference.
In tests, vaccinated mice, which were subsequently supplied with nicotine, continued their normal activities.
But mice that weren’t vaccinated “calmed down,” the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given so often as to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies that they proved to be expensive and impractical.
The cost of a new vaccine should be much lower, as it converts liver cells into factories producing antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
However, it is much more likely that smokers would use it to stop.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them get rid of that bad habit,” he said.
