With the growing poverty of the middle class, pawnshops in Singapore are booming
At a pawnshop in Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga stops a gold bracelet, ring and earrings so she can pay her daughter’s tuition fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house and I put all my money into it,” says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she receives $2,400 ($3,000 SGD) each month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family’s monthly income is insufficient, she says.
Indeed, demand across areas in Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is such that ValueMax, where a woman is carrying out her transaction, has become the third pawnbroker on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Stopping jewelry is not only a quick way to borrow cash – SGD 1300 in the case of Ms. Amirthalinga – but it’s also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Pawnshops in Singapore routinely apply an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require verification of a person (payment history) or proof of income, and can provide a loan faster than banks.
And as families feel pressured by rising living costs and rising household debt and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans backed by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to deal with the deteriorating financial situation.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's cited the increasing use of credit in households mainly due to rising rents as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in terms of gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the forefront of the ranking with a ratio of 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists also feared the high levels of consumption debt in Thailand, which this week has just emerged from a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed continued weak exports and weakening consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that with rising costs, people from medium to low [income scale] will try to replenish their income wherever they can,” said Song Seng Wun, an economist at Malaysia’s CIMB Bank.
Historically high gold prices over the past two years have prompted people to swiftly seize their personal assets and seize the opportunity to exchange their family jewellery for cash.
About 70 percent of the items stopped in 200 city pawnshops are gold.
People say, the price of gold looks good, we stop Grandma's gold necklace and get it back next month.
Thailand’s largest pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in the number of customers using its pawnshop in recent months.
The growth in the mortgage industry is so great that ValueMax, the operator of a branch in the center of Bendemeer and 15 similar in Singapore, plans to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where it has four branches – but also outside Asia, says ValueMax Yeah CEO Lee Ching.
The company will finance this by using 60 percent of the SGD 66 million it raised on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
While some discount lenders have come under fire for high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the pledge not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but it also doesn’t directly increase debt.
“Customers are stopping items they already own, and monetizing personal property does not increase the household’s debt,” he says.
In society, a pledge of property is increasingly accepted as a means of securing short-term, secured financing.
Moreover, among those who use pawnshops, there are not only people in financial distress.
Rich people from Singapore also use ValueMax branches when stopping gold bars or Rolex watches, and can get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers are of all possible circumstances.
“These include wealthy individuals who need short-term borrowing because of their bold trades or investments, or small businesses who need help solving problems in their cash flow,” says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need the money as fast as possible.
