Scientists have more clarified how the movements of the tail are related to the mood of the dog
Previous research has shown that cheerful dogs swing their tails more to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs swing their tails mostly to the left.
But now scientists say other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right sides of the brain have different connections to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.”
We've tried to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs respond to the asymmetrical spin of other dogs’ tails, the researchers monitored animals who watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tails go one way and the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We screened dog films – either in a natural version or in a silhouette – to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail and portray it more to the right or left.”
When the animals saw an otherwise faint dog move its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog swinging its tail), it remained completely calm.
But when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog swinging the tail), their heart rate increased and the animals seemed uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn’t think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and need not watch out for.
He said: “If you encounter dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior, and movement to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you will react based on this experience.”
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand the emotions of their pets.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a college animal health teacher at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they observe an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a cheerful dog.
And in another treatise from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dog robots were more likely to get acquainted when they swing their tails to the left than to the right, when they were more likely to become insecure – quite the opposite of the Italian study.”
The difference may be due to the fact that the dogs in these different studies did not interpret the animals in the movies or the dog robots completely as dogs.
He explained that studies on how dogs react to real dogs could help.
“Although there is strong evidence in the case of many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail goes sometimes one way and sometimes the other.
