Obstructive Politics Cannot Excuse Obama’s Healthcare Website’s Trouble or Drone Attacks
Obama’s 2008 campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is studying medicine at Harvard University in his second year.
I am reading a very sad book these days.
I thought about this book that during the gloomy days of my second year at the medical school it would encourage me and renew a pinch of hope in me.
It’s called “The Audacity to Win” and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient reviews tonight and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelming supremacy, and television news forced us to reflect on the historical value of this moment.
My classmates cried with joy, and my parents kept the newspapers they got.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
When he took office in 2008, Obama had 82 percent support.
And here I close the book.
Going into the present is a rough awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic days—they seem to be distant memories, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I put in my first ballot, there have actually been changes.
It was definitely nothing I had imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied successes – from the Affordable Care Act to the removal of our troops from Iraq and the end of the policy of “no questions, no words” after the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that the party's obstructions have reversed so many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, the public's choice of health care, and the closure of the Guantánamo base, among others.
But after many situations in which I defended the Obama administration against colleagues and friends, I have reached an absolute limit in terms of the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political hopelessness.
The Republican obstruction cannot explain the consent to the wiretapping of foreign leaders or the drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain the fact that the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans, nor that it persecutes those who expose the wrongdoings of the government.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without due process, or for limiting public contributions and expenditures during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of the report, which says that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, they can not even apologize for the inability to create more than 3 years after the signing of the Affordable Care Act a simple website.
I don't know if that was to be expected.
Whether I should have suspected at the age of 18 that government power might be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
The elected office is clearly not predictable, and our public talks will be shaped by an opposition political party and random events like the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above seem to be largely the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unbroken alternative and seemed unable to consolidate his policy or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, freed from the pressure of the next election, would fill the hopes we once heard about.
Yet returning to 2008 – with Obama’s support falling below 45% this week – through this book is becoming increasingly difficult.
It reminds me of a series of promises that have vanished.
