Google, Samsung and Huawei sued over Nortel patents
The group, which holds thousands of patents for the defunct Nortel, filed a patent infringement lawsuit on Thursday against mobile phone makers, including Google, a company it auctioned off in the wake of Nortel’s bankruptcy.
The Rockstar consortium, which bought Nortel's $4.5 billion patents, has sued Samsung Electronics, HTC, Huawei and four other companies in Texas for patent infringement.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, Blackberry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google has been accused of infringing seven patents.
Patents include technology that helps link search terms to relevant ads, according to the lawsuit, which is at the heart of Google’s search business.
Representatives of Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar were not immediately reached.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC are making phones that run on Google’s Android operating system, which competes heavily with Apple’s and Microsoft’s mobile products.
In 2011, Google made an initial offer of $900 million for Nortel patents.
Google increased its bid several times and eventually offered up to $4.4 billion.
After Nortel was defeated by Rockstar in the patent battle, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a business driven in part by Motorola’s patent group.
“Despite its failure to obtain the patents at auction, Google has infringed the patents and continues to infringe them,” the lawsuit said.
Rockstar is seeking increased damages from Google because, according to the lawsuit, the patent was intentionally infringed by Google.
