Egypt announces first freely elected president
Mohamed Morsi has taken the inaugural oath, but his triumphant day will hardly put an end to the political unrest in Egypt.
Islamist Muhammad Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he was inaugurated as the country’s first freely elected president, after Husni Mubarak, who had been ousted 16 months earlier.
In his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He swore an oath in front of 18 judges dressed in black talars in a mansion built overlooking the Nile that resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are working for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“The Egyptian people today laid the foundation for a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer who studied in the United States and is a member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of fierce attacks by individual governments for most of its 84 years as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. local time in a small convoy of cars, hundreds of soldiers and police were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered in front of the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of the Mubarak period, traffic was only briefly stopped so that the column could pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs in the south.
Morsi’s personal prestige, ridiculously referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood’s non-charismatic “reserve tyre,” has risen sharply since his victory and Friday’s speech aimed at presenting him not only as an Islamist candidate, but also for all those who want to end the rebellion against authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt is now a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Morsi said, wearing a blue social suit and a red tie in a wooden chamber where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to the University of Cairo to deliver his inaugural speech.
While standing alert, he received an official welcome from a military band that played the national anthem.
The military commander, Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi, was present.
His arrival was accompanied by the chanting “the army and the people are one hand” from the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
The University of Cairo was founded in 1908 as a centre of secular education and later in the 1970s became a bastion of the Islamic student movement.
Morsi took a symbolic oath Friday in Tahrir Square, where the revolution that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year was born, and vowed to retake the presidential powers taken from his office by the military council that took them from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to make an official oath before the court, rather than before parliament, as is customary, he yielded to the will of the army, indicating that the struggle for power would continue.
Mursi’s speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
