The Coal Hill is a remnant of a young volcano.
Although the data from radiometric age measurements vary slightly, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than the Great Roudny (aged 3.3 million years) and older than the Venus Volcano (aged 0.8 million years).
The volcano was born from an explosion.
It ejected a considerable amount of volcanic ash along with fragments of rock from the substrate, which became reddish-brown when burned.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters strong.
The second eruption erupted red, brown-red and sometimes black tuffs.
Their layer is powerful up to 50 meters, and part of it is accessible in the wall of the quarry.
In the tuffs are noticeable volcanic bombs up to 1 meter in size. The second eruption ended with a lava eruption.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which today forms a powerful layer of slag basalt up to 50 m.
Volcanoes in which volcanic ash eruptions alternate with lava flows are the most common type of volcano.
Because they are actually composed of layers, they are called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone gradually underwent erosion.
However, he was threatened only by the extraction of rocks in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in 1953 - 1962.
Tuffs were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
The mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public, thus preserving this unique place.
The problem, however, is the porosity and small cohesion of the rocks, which quickly weather, decay and slide down the slope.
The fracture disappears quite quickly.
To make the situation even more complicated, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal place for some rare species of plants and animals.
Correction is therefore problematic, but over time it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
