For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if doctors could visit Cameroon, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his countrymen suffering, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on weekends, where they provide free medical care.
Since 2008, almost 32,000 people have helped with their group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people cram into vans, attach medical supplies to rooftops, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need of help.
They are not always accompanied by luck.
More than once they have to push vehicles through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed as real heroes: a feast, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is indeed a reason to celebrate, and Bwelle – with his broad smile and unbridled energy – is very eager to join in the local cheerfulness.
The next day, the team starts treating hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on each expedition," Bwelle says.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide different medical care.
Many are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches or donated glasses or a birth certificate for free – a document that many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs a simple operation under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually done in a school building, town hall or at home; after the operation, the patient gets up and goes to a recovery site to free up space for another patient.
With the help of light from the generator, operating room and hygiene equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It’s exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team not to lose motivation.
"To stay up and keep working, they play the drums all night," Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team heads back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group – consisting of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students – performed 700 surgeries for free last year and is aware that their help can mean a lot to local residents.
One man said he would be able to work again after hernia surgery.
"It will change the future of our family," the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private medical clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says that this second work finances about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
“I’m not sure when he’s actually sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and works as a volunteer for Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley who came from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it’s a great practice they wouldn’t get at home.
"We washed Dr. Bwell's hands thoroughly and removed blood stains or held his tools," O'Malley said.
You’ll never experience that as a second-year medical student in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for a trip to Cameroon on their own and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive at Yaounde, Bwelle provides them with food, transportation, and study.
"He's a hero, no doubt," O'Malley says.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, constant harnessing is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling a promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job," Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Make people laugh, ease their pain – that’s why I do it.
Take a look at the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
