Australian Woman Appeals Against Thai Prison
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, who was sentenced to 15 days in prison on the island of Phuket after falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially indicted on June 15 by a provincial court on the island of Phuket on false charges when she told Thai police that the taxi driver, along with two other men who allegedly detained her, assaulted her in the early hours of Sunday, June 10.
However, an industrial television footage later revealed that after she broke up with her Australian boyfriend, she returned safely to her hotel.
Phuket Island police interviewed Bamford for two days before she confessed to making up the story.
Before the trial, she was held in a local police cell.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security correctional facility on the outskirts of Phuket, instead of being placed in an adult women’s prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian league player Peter Tunks, who asked the Canberra Department of State for help in his daughter's case.
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph that the entire family was “extremely worried” about their daughter’s fate and wanted her back in Australia.
"Obviously it's a difficult time, but we hope they will return to us safely as soon as possible," Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the verdict and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
Reports from Australia indicate that in the meantime she was spending holidays in the Krabi recreation area in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand claim that Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but she was warned that the appeal could lead to legal proceedings that would increase her sentence and result in her being placed in an adult prison.
But after the recent murder of Australian travel agency employee Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also be trying to fix a bruised image for tourists, which may have just been behind the acquittal.
